<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-487-512  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 487 512.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  July 20 1989 v15 n15 p21(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Out of the lab and into production; the current state-of-the-artin expert systems and natural languages.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Harris, Larry R.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>State-of-the-art commercial expert systems are able to interfacewith data base management systems on many different levels.andP;  Theexpert system's IF THEN rules are allowed to define patterns thatwill be matched against data base records, so that only thoserecords that match the pattern are read into the memory.andP;  Many ofthe newest artificial intelligence tools use the same centralserver architecture employed by most data base management systemsto interface with a teleprocessing monitor.andP;  State-of-the-artnatural language systems allow nearly every data base to beaccessed using ordinary English.andP;  The advantage of naturallanguage tools is that they can easily handle complex datastructures.andP;  Expert systems and natural language applications arebeing combined to develop artificial intelligence far beyond whatit was just a few years ago.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Artificial IntelligenceNatural Language InterfacesData Base Management SystemsData ProcessingExpert Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>